 to retain 100 digits in the expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2\ell}{\pi h}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is however another more subtle assumption of unbounded computational
 power in the experiment.
 We are assuming that we can always determine with certainty whether a needle
 is crossing a line.
 But 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lines
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on the the floor have thickness, their distance apart is not exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, and the needles lengths are not all absolutely equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

.
 These perturbations make the events 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fuzzy.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Thus, in an experiment with limited resources, it is not possible to talk
 about the idealized event that exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 needles cross lines as this would require the most expensive needles built
 to the most precise accuracy, laser precision for drawing lines on the
 floor, and the most powerful microscopes to determine if a needle does
 cross a line.
 Instead we might talk about the event that 
\begin_inset Formula $M-\delta$
\end_inset

 needles evidently cross lines and 
\begin_inset Formula $M+\delta'$
\end_inset

 needles plausibly cross lines where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta'$
\end_inset

 are resource-dependent approximations.
 This fuzzy notion of events leads to probabilities being only calculable
 within intervals of confidence reflecting the certainty of events and their
 plausibility.
 This is indeed consistent with published experiments: in an experiment
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $3204$
\end_inset

 needles and the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\ell}{h}=0.6$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeMorgan1872"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $1213$
\end_inset

 needles clearly crossed a line and 
\begin_inset Formula $11$
\end_inset

 needles were close enough to plausibly be considered as crossing the line:
 we would express the probability in this case as the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\frac{1213}{3204},\frac{1224}{3204}\right]$
\end_inset

 expressing that we are certain that the event has probability at least
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1213}{3204}$
\end_inset

 but it is possible that it would have probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1224}{3204}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

