\begin_layout Standard
Recall that classical probability measure can be constructed from its Radon-Niko
dym derivative.
 Similarly, a quantum probability measure can be easily constructed by states
 according to the Born rule
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Born1983,Mermin2007,RiederSvozil2007"

\end_inset

.
 For each pure normalized (
\begin_inset Formula $\ip{\phi}{\phi}=1$
\end_inset

) quantum state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\phi}$
\end_inset

, the Born rule induces a probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\phi}^{B}$
\end_inset

 as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{\phi}^{B}(P)=\ip{\phi}{P\phi}\textrm{ .}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, the Born rule can be extended to a mixed state.
 When we prepare a state, suppose the probability of preparing state
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\phi_{j}}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

, the state of the system can be expressed as a density matrix
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\sum_{j=1}^{N}q_{j}\proj{\phi_{j}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j=1}^{N}q_{j}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then, the quantum probability measure introduced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is the combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\phi_{j}}^{B}$
\end_inset

 with respect to probability 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "peres1995quantum,544199,RiederSvozil2007"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mu_{\rho}^{B}\left(P\right) & = & \Tr\left(\rho P\right)=\sum_{j=1}^{N}q_{j}\mu_{\phi_{j}}^{B}\left(P\right)\textrm{ .}\label{BornRule.mixed}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that the mixed state
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

